h3. Issue Summary
When using JIRA Service Desk with Confluence to have a knowledge base, we have the possibility to create awesome documents for our customers.
Though, when we are creating these articles in Confluence, depending on how the macros are set there, JIRA won't load the articles the way we expect.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# From Confluence, create a page called *Excerpt macro* in your space that is linked to your JIRA SD project as a knowledge base;
# Take a screenshot of anywhere in this page;
# Call the *Excerpt* macro and paste the image within the macro;
# Publish the page;
# Create a new page in this same space called *Excerpt Include*;
# Call the *Excerpt Include* macro and fill the field with the page we created before: *Excerpt macro*;
# Publish the page;
# Go to your Customer Portal or even the Knowledge Base section of your Service Desk project and open the page *Excerpt Include*.

h3. Expected Results
The page loads fine with its original content.

h3. Actual Results
The content from within the *Excerpt Include* macro doesn't show the image - it shows a broken icon instead.
* The same behavior is observed if we use the *Include Page* macro.

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary

If you create a "Flag" (using the AP.flag.create() method) that contains an Action, you can listen to the action using AP.events.on('flag.action', f)
 However, if you create the Flag on a "Legacy Issue View" of a Service Desk request _reached through the SD queue_, the event is never triggered. Instead, the page is reloaded.
h3. Steps to Reproduce

When viewing a request through the queue's
 # Create a Web Panel with a _'atl.jira.view.issue.left.context'_ location
 # In the web panel, add the following script:
{code:java}
<script>
AP.flag.create({
  type: 'warning',
  title: "Hi",
  actions: {"actionId":"Action Title"}
});

AP.events.on('flag.action', function(e){
  console.debug("flag action clicked");
});
</script>
{code}

 # Go to a SD request through the *Queue*. Example URL:
{code:java}
https://test.atlassian.net/jira/servicedesk/projects/SD/queues/custom/33/SD-1?oldIssueView=true
{code}

 # Click on the Flag's _"Action Title"_ link
 # You'll see the request being reloaded, instead of "flag action clicked" being logged

 

However, if you navigate to the issue directly from Jira:
{code:java}
https://test.atlassian.net/browse/SD-1?oldIssueView=true
{code}
it will work. Likewise if you use the New Issue view.
h3. Expected Results

Page does not reload and the event being fired and subsequently captured. Which will result in a console log of _"flag action clicked"_
h3. Actual Results

Page reloads
h3. Workaround

None

h3. Issue Summary

Number field in the customer portal is shown without a floating-point separator, different behavior from the issue view.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a custom field with the number field type;
 # Add this field to create/edit/view screens in a Service Desk project;
 # Open a request using this number field, for example, 123456789;
 # In the issue view the floating-point will appear, separating the numbers;
 # In the customer portal the number will show without the separator;

h3. Expected Results

The floating-point will appear in the number field when necessary.
h3. Actual Results

The floating-point doesn't appear, treating the field as text.
h3. Workaround

Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available
h3. Additional Information

Browser Used: Google Chrome and Safari.
{code:html}
<div data-test-id="request-details.text-field">123456789</div>{code}

h3. Issue Summary
In a Service Desk Next-Gen project if the internal access is Open a user inside a role without any permission can execute most of the features (assign, edit, transition, etc).

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a Next-Gen Service Desk project;
 # In Project Settings > Internal Access > Change Internal Access, leave it Open;
 # On Manage Roles create a new role without any access permission;
 # Add a user to only this role;

h3. Expected Results
The user wouldn't be able to use the features he doesn't have access to.

h3. Actual Results
The user will be able to edit, assign, transition and other functionalities. 

h3. Workaround
Change the Internal Access to Private that will respect the permissions defined in the role.
